252B.description: Applications of organometallic compounds in synthesis with an emphasis on catalysis.
252B.title: Organometallic Chemistry II

104A.description: The chemistry of metals and nonmetals including the application of physical chemical principles.
104A.title: Advanced Inorganic Chemistry

299.description: The facilities of the laboratory are available at all times to graduate students pursuing original investigations toward an advanced degree at this University. Such work is ordinarily in collaboration with a member of the staff.
299.title: Research for Graduate Students

120A.description: Kinetic, potential, and total energy of particles and forces between them; principles of quantum theory, including one-electron and many-electron atoms and its applications to chemical bonding, intermolecular interactions, and elementary spectroscopy.
120A.title: Physical Chemistry

220A.description: A rigorous presentation of classical thermodynamics followed by an introduction to statistical mechanics with the application to real systems.
220A.title: Thermodynamics and Statistical Mechanics

96.description: Introduces freshmen to research activities and programs of study in the College of Chemistry. Includes lectures by faculty, an introduction to college library and computer facilities, the opportunity to meet alumni and advanced undergraduates in an informal atmosphere, and discussion of college and campus resources.
96.title: Introduction to Research and Study in the College of Chemistry

3A.description: Introduction to organic chemical structures, bonding, and chemical reactivity. The organic chemistry of alkanes, alkyl halides, alcohols, alkenes, alkynes, and organometallics.
3A.title: Chemical Structure and Reactivity

195.description: Special topics will be offered from time to time. Examples are: photochemical air pollution, computers in chemistry.
195.title: Special Topics

295.description: Lecture series on topics of current interest. Recently offered topics: Natural products synthesis, molecular dynamics, statistical mechanics, molecular spectroscopy, structural biophysics, organic polymers, electronic structure of molecules and bio-organic chemistry.
295.title: Special Topics

301B.description: Tutoring of students in 1A-1B. Students attend a weekly meeting on tutoring methods at the Student Learning Center and attend 1A-1B lectures.
301B.title: Undergraduate Chemistry Instruction

1A.description: Stoichiometry of chemical reactions, quantum mechanical description of atoms, the elements and periodic table, chemical bonding, real and ideal gases, thermochemistry, introduction to thermodynamics and equilibrium, acid-base and solubility equilibria, introduction to oxidation-reduction reactions, introduction to chemical kinetics.
1A.title: General Chemistry

196.description: Special laboratory work for advanced undergraduates.
196.title: Special Laboratory Study

300.description: Discussion, curriculum development, class observation, and practice teaching in chemistry.
300.title: Professional Preparation: Supervised Teaching of Chemistry

260.description: Advanced methods for studying organic reaction mechanisms. Topics include kinetic isotope effects, behavior of reactive intermediates, chain reactions, concerted reactions, molecular orbital theory and aromaticity, solvent and substituent effects, linear free energy relationships, photochemistry.
260.title: Reaction Mechanisms

103.description: The basic principles of metal ions and coordination chemistry applied to the study of biological systems.
103.title: Inorganic Chemistry in Living Systems

113.description: Advanced topics in mechanistic and physical organic chemistry typically including kinetics, reactive intermediates, substitution reactions, linear free energy relationships, orbital interactions and orbital symmetry control of reactions, isotope effects, and photochemistry.
113.title: Advanced Mechanistic Organic Chemistry

H193.description: A senior honors thesis is written in consultation with the student’s faculty research advisor. This is a required course for students wishing to graduate with honors in Chemistry or Chemical Biology.
H193.title: Senior Honors Thesis

298.description: In addition to the weekly Graduate Research Conference and weekly seminars on topics of interest in biophysical, organic, physical, nuclear, and inorganic chemistry, there are group seminars on specific fields of research. Seminars will be announced at the beginning of each semester.
298.title: Seminars for Graduate Students

251A.description: Structure and bonding, synthesis, and reactions of the d-transition metals and their compounds.
251A.title: Coordination Chemistry I

C130.description: Thermodynamic and kinetic concepts applied to understanding the chemistry and structure of biomolecules (proteins, DNA, and RNA). Molecular distributions, reaction kinetics, enzyme kinetics. Bioenergetics, energy transduction, and motor proteins. Electrochemical potential, membranes, and ion channels.
C130.title: Biophysical Chemistry: Physical Principles and the Molecules of Life

197.description: Supervised experience in off-campus organizations relevant to specific aspects and applications of chemistry. Written report required at the end of the term. Course does not satisfy unit or residence requirements for the bachelor's degree.
197.title: Field Study in Chemistry

250A.description: An introduction to group theory, symmetry, and representations as applied to chemical bonding.
250A.title: Introduction to Bonding Theory

3AL.description: Introduction to the theory and practice of methods used in the organic chemistry laboratory. An emphasis is placed on the separation and purification of organic compounds. Techniques covered will include extraction, distillation, sublimation, recrystalization, and chromatography. Detailed discussions and applications of infrared and nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy will be included.
3AL.title: Organic Chemistry Laboratory

201.description: Review of bonding, structure, MO theory, thermodynamics, and kinetics.
201.title: Fundamentals of Inorganic Chemistry

143.description: Radioactivity, fission, nuclear models and reactions, nuclear processes in nature. Computer methods will be introduced.
143.title: Nuclear Chemistry

192.description: All properly qualified students who wish to pursue a problem of their own choice, through reading or nonlaboratory study, may do so if their proposed project is acceptable to the member of the staff with whom they wish to work.
192.title: Individual Study for Advanced Undergraduates

98W.description: Topics vary with instructor. Enrollment restrictions apply.
98W.title: Directed Group Study

3BL.description: The synthesis and purification of organic compounds will be explored. Natural product chemistry will be introduced. Advanced spectroscopic methods including infrared, ultraviolet, and nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy and mass spectrometry will be used to analyze products prepared and/or isolated. Qualitative analysis of organic compounds will be covered.
3BL.title: Organic Chemistry Laboratory

301D.description: Tutoring of students enrolled in an undergraduate chemistry course.
301D.title: Undergraduate Chemistry Course Instruction

135.description: One-semester introduction to biochemistry, aimed toward chemistry and chemical biology majors.
135.title: Chemical Biology

199.description: Enrollment is restricted by regulations listed in the <General Catalog>.
199.title: Supervised Independent Study and Research

3B.description: Conjugation, aromatic chemistry, carbonyl compounds, carbohydrates, amines, carboxylic acids, amino acids, peptides, proteins, and nucleic acid chemistry. Ultraviolet spectroscopy and mass spectrometry will be introduced.
3B.title: Chemical Structure and Reactivity

108.description: The preparation of inorganic compounds using vacuum line, air-and moisture-exclusion, electrochemical, high-pressure, and other synthetic techniques. Kinetic and mechanistic studies of inorganic compounds.
108.title: Inorganic Synthesis and Reactions

261A.description: Features of the reactions that comprise the vocabulary of synthetic organic chemistry.
261A.title: Organic Reactions I

265.description: The theory behind practical nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy and a survey of its applications to chemical research.
265.title: Nuclear Magnetic Resonance Theory and Application

261B.description: More reactions that are useful to the practice of synthetic organic chemistry.
261B.title: Organic Reaction II

301.description: Provides training and opportunity for graduate students to make presentations in local public schools. Training ensures that presenters are aware of scientific information mandated by the State of California for particular grade levels, and that presentations are intellectually stimulating, relevant to the classroom students' interests, and age-appropriate. Time commitment an average of two to three hours/week, but actual time spent is concentrated during preparation and classroom delivery of presentations, which are coordinated between teachers' needs and volunteers' availability.
301.title: Pre-High School Chemistry Classroom Immersion

221A.description: Introduction, one dimensional problems, matrix mechanics, approximation methods.
221A.title: Advanced Quantum Mechanics

49.description: Students with partial credit in lower division chemistry courses may, with consent of instructor, complete the credit under this heading.
49.title: Supplementary Work in Lower Division Chemistry

301C.description: Undergraduate organic lab assistants help in the teaching of the 3AL and 3BL. Each week students attend a laboratory preparation meeting for one hour, assist in the laboratory section for four hours, and help in the development of experiments for one hour.
301C.title: Chemistry 3 Lab Assistant

15.description: An introduction to analytical and bioanalytical chemistry including background in statistical analysis of data, acid-base equilibria, electrochemical, spectrometric, and chromatographic methods of analysis and some advanced topics in bioanalytical chemistry such as micro-fluidics, bioassay techniques, and enzymatic biosensors.
15.title: Analytical and Bioanalytical Chemistry

149.description: Students with partial credit in upper division chemistry courses may, with consent of instructor, complete the credit under this heading.
149.title: Supplementary Work in Upper Division Chemistry

1AL.description: An experimental approach to chemical sciences with emphasis on developing fundamental, reproducible laboratory technique and a goal of understanding and achieving precision and accuracy in laboratory experiments. Proper use of laboratory equipment and standard wet chemical methods are practiced. Areas of investigations include chemical equilibria, spectroscopy, nanotechnology, green chemistry, and thermochemistry. Concurrent enrollment in 1A is recommended.
1AL.title: General Chemistry Laboratory

125.description: Experiments in thermodynamics, kinetics, molecular structure, and general physical chemistry.
125.title: Physical Chemistry Laboratory

112A.description: A study of all aspects of fundamental organic chemistry, including nomenclature, chemical and physical properties, reactions and syntheses of the major classes of organic compounds. The study includes theoretical aspects, reaction mechanisms, multistep syntheses, and the chemistry of polycyclic and heterocyclic compounds. This course is more extensive and intensive than 3A-3B and includes a greater emphasis on reaction mechanisms and multistep syntheses. 112A (F); 112B (SP)
112A.title: Organic Chemistry

301W.description: Tutoring of students in the College of Chemistry Scholars Program who are enrolled in general or organic chemistry. Students attend a weekly meeting with instructors.
301W.title: Supervised Instruction of Chemistry Scholars

120B.description: Statistical mechanics, thermodynamics, equilibrium and applications to chemical systems: states of matter, solutions and solvation, chemical kinetics, molecular dynamics, and molecular transport.
120B.title: Physical Chemistry

301A.description: Tutoring of students in 1AL and 1B laboratory. Students attend one hour of the regular GSI preparatory meeting and hold one office hour per week to answer questions about laboratory assignments.
301A.title: Undergraduate Lab Instruction

115.description: Advanced synthetic methods, chemical and spectroscopic structural methods, designed as a preparation for experimental research.
115.title: Organic Chemistry--Advanced Laboratory Methods

122.description: Postulates and methods of quantum mechanics and group theory applied to molecular structure and spectra.
122.title: Quantum Mechanics and Spectroscopy

4A.description: This series is intended for majors in physical and biological sciences and in engineering. It presents the foundation principles of chemistry, including stoichiometry, ideal and real gases, acid-base and solubility equilibria, oxidation-reduction reactions, thermochemistry, entropy, nuclear chemistry and radioactivity, the atoms and elements, the periodic table, quantum theory, chemical bonding, molecular structure, chemical kinetics, and descriptive chemistry. Examples and applications will be drawn from diverse areas of special interest such as atmospheric, environmental, materials, polymer and computational chemistry, and biochemistry. Laboratory emphasizes quantitative work. Equivalent to 1A-1B plus 15 as prerequisite for further courses in chemistry.
4A.title: General Chemistry and Quantitative Analysis

H194.description: Students may pursue original research under the direction of one of the members of the staff.
H194.title: Research for Advanced Undergraduates

252A.description: An introduction to organometallics, focusing on structure, bonding, and reactivity.
252A.title: Organometallic Chemistry I

200.description: Review of bonding, structure, stereochemistry, conformation, thermodynamics and kinetics, and arrow-pushing formalisms.
200.title: Chemistry Fundamentals
